space shuttle disaster may lead to suspension of space station : russian expert
( afp report from moscow ) a russian space expert pointed out that the unfortunate incident of the disintegration of the us space shuttle the us space shuttle on its way back to the earth might result in a temporary halt to the artificial missions of the international space station carried out by the us space shuttle and russian spacecraft .
the russian space expert , who wanted to be named , told the interfax news agency that the accident of the disintegration of the colombian bihar on its return to the atmosphere would force astronauts on the space station to return to the ground and open up the automatic system of the space station for some time .
he said that if the accident was confirmed to be caused by the age of the shuttle , the united states would freeze all mission to the space shuttle so as to avoid a recurrence of similar disasters .
he further pointed out that the united states is likely to send astronauts to the space station in 2007 or 2008 and to build a new spacecraft .
if the us space shuttle stops , russia will only send astronauts to the space station . however , the russian space agency is facing serious financial difficulties . therefore , the united states and russia may reach an agreement to use the united states to maintain the man - made task of the space station and use the ship carrier to transport the international space station .
the russian expert said that astronauts on the international space station should continue to stay on the space station now that they were due to return to the earth by the us space shuttle atlanta on march 1 .
the international space station program involves 16 countries , including the united states , russia , japan , canada , and france .
russian experts pointed out that the unfortunate one - day event showed that the shuttle was unreliable . in 1971 , russia also had an accident in which the joint no . 11 spaceship crashed while returning to the earth , damaging three astronauts aboard the spacecraft .
