us defense department lifts two missile interception tests
xinhua news agency , washington , january 8 ( reporter : tan xinmu ) - a spokesman for the us defense department 's missile defense agency announced on the 8 th that the us military had decided to cancel the two missile interception tests scheduled for the first half of this year because the new type of missile - interceptor missile had fallen behind the original development process .
aznar told the press that the missile defense department needs to concentrate efforts on solving the problem of the rocket , and that the next missile interception test will be carried out after the boeing company produces a new type of rocket this autumn .
the boeing company originally planned to begin its flight testing of the new type of boost rocket carrying " interceptor " missiles in 2000 , but the test was postponed due to technical reasons .
the boeing company decided to re - design the rocket after it failed in december 2001 and is scheduled to complete it this autumn .
in the eight land - based missile interception tests that have already been carried out , the us military used modified " militia " rocket as a substitute for boosters , but the test results of this type of boosters are not ideal .
both the missile interception tests conducted in july 2000 and december last year failed because the " interceptor " failed to separate from the interceptor missile .
on 17 december last year , us president bush ordered the department of defense to start deploying the missile defense system in order to build a preliminary missile defense system by september 2004 .
however , many experts believe that technically speaking , the time is not yet ripe for deploying the missile defense system .
kadish , director of the missile defense agency , also said that the deployment of the entire missile defense system would be affected if the boeing company fails to produce a qualified boost rocket as scheduled .
